{"title_page": "Tears on the Dancefloor", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Tears on the Dancefloor\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Steps (group)|Steps]]\n| cover      = Steps - Tears on the Dancefloor (Official Album Cover).png\n| border     = yes\n| alt        = Head shots of five people with a mirrored, upside down reflection of themselves, with an alternate facial expression.\n| released   = {{Start date|2017|04|21|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = October 2016\u2013Early 2017\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = {{Duration|m=37|s=36}}\n| label      = \n*Absolute\n*[[Fascination Records|Fascination]]\n| producer   = \n*The Alias \n*Carl Ryden\n*[[Brian Rawling]]\n| prev_title = [[Light Up the World (Steps album)|Light Up the World]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[Tears on the Dancefloor#Crying at the Disco reissue|Tears on the Dancefloor: Crying at the Disco]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Tears on the Dancefloor\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Scared of the Dark]]\n | single1date = 10 March 2017\n | single2     = [[Story of a Heart (song)|Story of a Heart]]\n | single2date = 12 May 2017\n | single3     = [[Neon Blue]]\n | single3date = 4 August 2017\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[Daily Express]]''\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Daily Express Tears on the Dancefloor Review\">{{cite web|last=Kitchener|first=Shaun|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/music/794604/Steps-Tears-on-the-Dancefloor-album-review|title=Steps: Tears on the Dancefloor Review - Pop legends cement comeback with glorious album|work=[[Daily Express]]|date=21 April 2017|accessdate=21 April 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6pszMpg0J?url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/music/794604/Steps-Tears-on-the-Dancefloor-album-review|archivedate=21 April 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"The Guardian Tears on the Dancefloor Review\">{{cite web|last=Davies|first=Hannah J|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/apr/20/steps-tears-on-the-dancefloor-review|title=Steps: Tears on the Dancefloor review \u2013 bolshy pop with new energy|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=20 April 2017|accessdate=21 April 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6pszFyR6U?url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/apr/20/steps-tears-on-the-dancefloor-review|archivedate=21 April 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Huffington Post]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"The Huffington Post Tears on the Dancefloor Review\">{{cite web|last=Bagwell|first=Matt|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/steps-tears-on-the-dancefloor-review-track-by-track_uk_58f88c51e4b0cb086d7e41dd|title=Steps \u2018Tears On the Dancefloor\u2019 Review: Our Track-By-Track Verdict|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=20 April 2017|accessdate=21 April 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6pszMpg0J?url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/music/794604/Steps-Tears-on-the-Dancefloor-album-review|archivedate=21 April 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Renowned for Sound]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Renowned for Sound Tears on the Dancefloor Review\">{{cite web|last=Veevers|first=Brandon|url=http://renownedforsound.com/index.php/album-review-steps-tears-on-the-dancefloor/|title=Album Review: Tears On The Dancefloor|work=[[Renowned for Sound]]|date=19 April 2017|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Tears on the Dancefloor''''' is the fifth [[studio album]] by British group [[Steps (group)|Steps]]. It was released on 21 April 2017, by Absolute and [[Fascination Records]]. Following two years of planning, recording began in October 2016. The Alias was enlisted to serve as the executive producer for ''Tears on the Dancefloor'' and various songwriters submitted songs for the group to record, including [[Steve Mac]], [[Ina Wroldsen]], [[TMS (production team)|TMS]] and [[Fiona Bevan]]. It also features a [[cover version]] of \"[[Story of a Heart (song)|Story of a Heart]]\" by [[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]] and [[Benny Andersson]] of [[ABBA]], a cover of \"[[I Will Love Again]]\" by [[Lara Fabian]] as well as a cover of \"No More Tears on the Dancefloor\" by [[Thomas Anders|Anders]]|[[J\u00f6rn-Uwe Fahrenkrog-Petersen|Fahrenkrog]]<!-- \"Anders|Fahrenkrog\" That is how it is spelled. With the | between the names.  -->, from which the album's title is derived.\n\nThe album was re-released on 27 October 2017 as ''Tears on the Dancefloor: Crying at the Disco'' with five new songs, three of which have accompanying remixes.<ref name=\"OCC Deluxe 1\">{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Rob|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/steps-to-re-release-their-latest-album-tears-on-the-dancefloor-with-five-new-songs__20450/|title=Steps to re-release their latest album Tears On The Dancefloor with five new songs|work=Official Charts Company|date=18 September 2017|accessdate=19 September 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919234318/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/steps-to-re-release-their-latest-album-tears-on-the-dancefloor-with-five-new-songs__20450/|archivedate=19 September 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Background and release==\nIn 2011, [[Steps (group)|Steps]] reunited for a four-part documentary series, which aired on [[Sky Living]].<ref name=\"DS 1\">{{cite web|last=Eamses|first=Tom|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a330859/steps-to-reunite-for-sky-living-documentary-series/|title=Steps to reunite for Sky Living documentary series|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=21 July 2011|accessdate=8 March 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6oo3BYmV0?url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a330859/steps-to-reunite-for-sky-living-documentary-series/|archivedate=8 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Documenting their highly publicised and acrimonious split on Boxing Day in 2001, it revealed what each member had been doing for the previous ten years, as well as reflecting on their time in the group and the truth, causes and effects of their disbandment.<ref name=\"DS 1\"/> It further showed how they could repair their professional, and personal, relationships as a five-piece for the release of their second [[Greatest hits album|greatest hits]] album, ''[[The Ultimate Collection (Steps album)|The Ultimate Collection]]'' (2011), and discussions of officially reforming.<ref name=\"DS 1\"/> The positive response to the album led to the announcement of a reunion arena tour, [[The Ultimate Tour (Steps)|The Ultimate Tour]], in April 2012,<ref name=\"DS 2\">{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Robert|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a344731/steps-announce-first-arena-tour-in-ten-years/|title=Steps announce first arena tour in ten years|work=Digital Spy|date=11 October 2011|accessdate=8 March 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6oo4AYztH?url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a344731/steps-announce-first-arena-tour-in-ten-years/|archivedate=8 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and their fourth studio/first Christmas album, ''[[Light Up the World (Steps album)|Light Up the World]]'', later that year. On 28 November 2016, it was revealed that Steps would be performing at [[G-A-Y]] on New Year's Eve to celebrate twenty years since their debut.<ref name=\"OCC 1\">{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Robert|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/steps-are-reuniting-for-a-new-years-eve-gig-to-celebrate-their-20th-anniversary__17247/|title=Steps are reuniting for a New Year's Eve gig to celebrate their 20th anniversary|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=28 November 2016|accessdate=8 March 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6oo5NRsFh?url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/steps-are-reuniting-for-a-new-years-eve-gig-to-celebrate-their-20th-anniversary__17247/|archivedate=8 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March 2017, Steps confirmed that their fifth studio album, ''Tears on the Dancefloor'', would be released on 21 April in the United Kingdom and be preceded by the lead single, \"[[Scared of the Dark]]\", on 10 March; they also announced the [[Party on the Dancefloor Tour]], which will take place in November and December 2017.<ref name=\"OCC 2\">{{cite web|last=White|first=Jack|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/steps-announce-comeback-album-tears-on-the-dancefloor-to-commemorate-their-20th-anniversary__18407/|title=Steps announce comeback album Tears on the Dancefloor to commemorate their 20th anniversary|work=Official Charts Company|date=6 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6oo5uG8xr?url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/steps-announce-comeback-album-tears-on-the-dancefloor-to-commemorate-their-20th-anniversary__18407/|archivedate=8 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In an interview for the [[Official Charts Company]] in March 2017, band member [[Faye Tozer]] confirmed The Alias as the producer for ''Tears on the Dancefloor'', while [[Lisa Scott-Lee]] revealed that planning the album had taken two years in an interview for [[Popjustice]].<ref name=\"OCC Tozer Interview\">{{cite web|last=Copsey|first=Rob|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/steps-faye-tozer-interview-this-is-all-about-getting-people-back-on-the-dance-floor__18418/|title=Steps' Faye Tozer interview: 'This is all about getting people back on the dance floor'|work=Official Charts Company|date=6 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NME Lisa Interview\">{{cite web|last=Trendell|first=Andrew|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/steps-return-20th-anniversary-tour-2003700|title=Steps return for new album and 20th anniversary tour|work=[[NME]]|date=6 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref> It is their first album to be composed of mostly original material in seventeen years; ''Light Up the World'' was composed of both cover and original songs, and was their first studio album in twelve years.<ref name=\"OCC 2\"/><ref name=\"EF 1\">{{cite web|last=Ellwood-Hughes|first=Pip|url=http://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/music-news/steps-to-mark-20th-anniversary-with-new-music-a-tour/|title=Steps to mark 20th anniversary with new music & a tour|work=Entertainment Focus|date=6 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6oo75G1Yw?url=http://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/music-news/steps-to-mark-20th-anniversary-with-new-music-a-tour/|archivedate=8 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Attitude 1\">{{cite web|last=Ellwood-Hughes|first=Pip|url=http://attitude.co.uk/steps-confirm-comeback-with-brand-new-single-album-and-tour/|title=Steps confirm comeback with new single, album and tour|work=[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]|date=6 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6oo7GGA06?url=http://attitude.co.uk/steps-confirm-comeback-with-brand-new-single-album-and-tour/|archivedate=8 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRecording for the album began in October 2016; Tozer revealed that the first two songs they recorded were omitted from the final track listing due to not sounding \"Steps-enough\".<ref name=\"OCC Tozer Interview\"/> Scott-Lee revealed that the group had recorded two albums' worth of material during the production of ''Tears on the Dancefloor'', but said that no formal discussions have taken place as to whether or not a sixth studio album will follow in 2018 despite reaffirming her personal desire to do so.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kelly|first=Emma|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/showbiz-tv/music/596249/Steps-for-Eurovision-20th-anniversary-comeback-Lisa-Scott-Lee-interview|title=Will Steps do Eurovision? Lisa Scott-Lee reveals all as band makes massive comeback|work=[[Daily Star (British newspaper)|Daily Star]]|date=13 March 2017|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> Three editions of ''Tears on the Dancefloor'' were made available to purchase on their website: a digital version available for download, a limited edition signed [[Compact disc|CD]] and a limited edition neon-blue [[Gramophone record|vinyl]].<ref name=\"UK Download Track listing Official Store\"/><ref name=\"UK Vinyl Track listing Official Store\"/><ref name=\"UK Signed Track listing Official Store\"/> The album artwork was inspired by the album cover of their debut album, ''[[Step One]]'' (1998).<ref name=\"Popjustice 1\">{{cite web|last=Robinson|first=Peter|url=https://www.popjustice.com/articles/lisa-scott-lee-interview-we-said-its-twenty-years-of-steps-what-can-we-do-to-make-it-special/|title=Lisa Scott-Lee interview: 'We said \u2014 it's twenty years of Steps, what can we do to make it special?'|work=[[Popjustice]]|date=6 March 2017|accessdate=8 March 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ooUr4cvn?url=https://www.popjustice.com/articles/lisa-scott-lee-interview-we-said-its-twenty-years-of-steps-what-can-we-do-to-make-it-special/|archivedate=8 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n===Music and lyrics===\nIn an interview with Popjustice, Scott-Lee stated that the group strived to create an uplifting, positive [[Pop music|pop]] album and to provide a form of escapism for listeners: \"We're not here to get into the politics of the world but what we can offer is escapism and a bit of positivity in people's lives.\"<ref name=\"OCC 2\"/><ref name=\"Popjustice 1\"/> She continued to elucidate that ''Tears on the Dancefloor'' sounds like where they should be twenty years on from their debut, saying \"Everyone's dealing with lots of different things but music's universal, and it takes you to another place and time, and this album \u2014 I feel \u2014 is where Steps ''should'' be twenty years on.\"<ref name=\"OCC 2\"/> Songwriters for the album include [[Steve Mac]], [[Ina Wroldsen]], [[TMS (production team)|TMS]], Carl Ryden, [[Fiona Bevan]], Kevin Verchel and Metrophonic.<ref name=\"Brighton Writers\">{{cite web|url=http://brightoncentre.co.uk/whats-on/2017/steps/|title=Steps|work=[[Brighton Centre]]|accessdate=8 March 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ooTX1dw7?url=http://brightoncentre.co.uk/whats-on/2017/steps/|archivedate=8 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The group took some inspiration from their back catalogue for the album, with Tozer saying that its sound is reminiscent of their single \"[[Deeper Shade of Blue]]\" (2000) but has more elements of [[dance music]].<ref name=\"OCC Tozer Interview\"/> They also revealed that the album consists of up-tempo songs with a couple of mid-tempo tracks, but no ballads, citing fans preferring their upbeat songs as their reason for deciding not to record any.<ref name=\"OCC Tozer Interview\"/>\n\n===Songs===\nThe lead single from the album, \"Scared of the Dark\", has been described by Popjustice as a \"robust blast of pop melodrama\", which they thought sounded as though it was lifted from their first greatest hits album, ''[[Gold: Greatest Hits (Steps album)|Gold: Greatest Hits]]'' (2001).<ref name=\"Popjustice 1\"/> Tozer revealed that a track called \"Neon Blue\" had been written by Ryden and Bevan, who have written songs for [[David Guetta]] and [[The Saturdays]], respectively. She continued to describe the track as \"nostalgic\" and a \"real homecoming type of song\".<ref name=\"OCC Tozer Interview\"/> Steps have also recorded a [[cover version]] of \"[[Story of a Heart (song)|Story of a Heart]]\" originally performed by [[Benny Anderssons orkester|Benny Anderssons Band]], and written and composed by [[Benny Andersson]] and [[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]] of [[ABBA]]. Scott-Lee stated that they have often been compared to ABBA and that Anderson and Ulvaeus had given it to them to record and that it serves as a \"perfect\" bridge to fill the gap between where they were as a group and where they are taking their music forward.<ref name=\"Attitude 1\"/>\n\n==Singles==\n\"[[Scared of the Dark]]\" premiered on ''[[Ken Bruce|The Ken Bruce Show]]'' on BBC Radio 2 on 9 March 2017,<ref name=\"Express SOTD Single Review\">{{cite web|last=Kitchener|first=Shaun|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/music/776992/Steps-Scared-of-the-Dark-review-clip-listen-stream-comeback-tour|title=Steps comeback single Scared Of The Dark REVIEW and clip: 'A glorious return'|work=[[Daily Express]]|date=9 March 2017|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> and was released on [[iTunes Store|iTunes]], [[Spotify]] and [[Apple Music]] the following day.<ref name=\"Single release dates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stepsofficial.co.uk/news/were-back-new-album-new-single-and-a-new-tour/|title=We're back! New album, new single and a new tour!|work=Steps Official|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> During a [[Facebook Live]] interview with ''[[HuffPost|HuffPost UK Entertainment]]'', [[Ian \"H\" Watkins]] announced that \"[[Story of a Heart (song)|Story of a Heart]]\" would be the album's second single.<ref>{{cite web|title=We are joined by the legendary pop group Steps. They'll be talking about the release of their second single|url=https://www.facebook.com/HuffPostUKEnt/videos/1755539481139907/|website=Facebook|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Tears on the Dancefloor''.<ref name=\"Tears on the Dancefloor Credits\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Tears on the Dancefloor|others=[[Steps (group)|Steps]]|year=2017|type=Liner notes|publisher=Steps Music LLP|id=}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Tears on the Dancefloor''<ref name=\"UK Download Track listing Official Store\"/><ref name=\"iTunes Album UK\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/tears-on-the-dancefloor/id1209587966|title=Tears on the Dancefloor|work=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 3