x3=April 4, 1957\n| OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1957|5|6}}\n| ShortSummary=Ricky has been chosen to dedicate a new [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]] statue in the [[Westport, Connecticut|Westport]] [[Town Square]]. There's a problem: Lucy has accidentally destroyed the one-of-a-kind sculpture. [[Desi Arnaz Jr.]] appears in the final crowd scene, his only appearance on the series.\n| LineColor=AE85CF\n}}\n}}\n\n==''The Lucy\u2013Desi Comedy Hour'' episodes==\nAfter season six, the series was renamed ''[[The Lucy\u2013Desi Comedy Hour|The Lucille Ball-Desi Arnaz Show]]'' for its original broadcast run and rather than airing as weekly half hour series, hour-long episodes were produced to run occasionally during the year. There were thirteen hour-long shows.  The first five were broadcast as specials during the 1957-58 television season.  The other eight episodes were broadcast as part of the ''[[Westinghouse Desilu Playhouse]]'' from October 6, 1958, to April 1, 1960. The series was subsequently broadcast in syndication as ''The Lucy-Desi Comedy Hour'' and ''We Love Lucy''. This show had the same cast as ''[[I Love Lucy]]'', employed many of the other same actors, and featured many famous guest stars.  Of the original ''I Love Lucy'' cast, besides the principals, only Lucy's mother appeared in any ''Comedy Hour'' episode.  She appears in season 3, episode 2 'The Ricardos Go To Japan' as Little Ricky's babysitter.\n\n===Season 1 (1957\u201358)===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF\"\n|- style=\"color:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#1B548A; width:25px\"| N\u00ba\n! style=\"background:#1B548A\"| Title \n! style=\"background:#1B548A; width:135px\"| Film date\n! style=\"background:#1B548A; width:135px\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H1\n| Title = Lucy Takes a Cruise to Havana\n| Aux3 = {{date|1957-6-28|mdy}}\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1957|11|6}}\n| ShortSummary = How did Lucy and Ricky meet? Well that's what Hollywood columnist (and special guest star) [[Hedda Hopper]] wants to know. In a flashback to 1940 we find Lucy McGillicuddy and her best friend Susie MacNamara (guest star [[Ann Sothern]] whose character makes a crossover appearance from her CBS show ''[[Private Secretary (TV series)|Private Secretary]]'') cruising Havana, where they encounter two tour guides, Ricky Ricardo and his pal, Carlos Garcia (guest star [[Cesar Romero]]). Plenty of Havana high-jinks soon ensue, with second honeymooners Fred and Ethel Mertz and popular crooner [[Rudy Vallee]] (as himself) along for the wild ride!\nNote: This was originally shown as a 75-minute episode. All future repeats were edited to an hour's length, with the original opening and closing sequences (featuring Hedda Hopper) deleted, replaced by Desi's brief narration at the beginning and end.\n| LineColor = 1B548A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H2\n| Title = The Celebrity Next Door\n| Aux3 = {{date|1957-9-27|mdy}}\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1957|12|3}}\n| ShortSummary = Who's the new resident moving into the house next to the Ricardos? None other than stage and screen star [[Tallulah Bankhead]]! Once Lucy discovers that a celebrity is in her midst, she tries to win her friendship by inviting her to an elegant dinner party\u2014with Fred and Ethel Mertz posing as hired help. Before long Lucy has gotten Ms. Bankhead and the entire gang involved with a local PTA show.\n[[Bette Davis]] was originally booked as the next-door celebrity, but suffered a horseback riding accident. Bankhead was the producers' second choice.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kanfer|first1=Stefan|title=Ball of Fire: The Tumultuous Life and Comic Art of Lucille Ball|date=2003|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|location=New York|isbn=0-375-41315-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/balloffiretumult00kanf/page/198 198]|ref=kanfer|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/balloffiretumult00kanf}}</ref>\n| LineColor = 1B548A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H3\n| Title = Lucy Hunts Uranium\n| Aux3 = {{date|1957-11-15|mdy}}<br> (Studio portions)\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1958|1|3}}\n| ShortSummary = Ricky and his band have been booked to play at the [[Sands Casino]] in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], and Lucy hopes the trip will allow her an opportunity to go uranium hunting. Fred and Ethel are keen on the idea but Ricky forbids it, until mysterious headlines put the entire town in a uranium uproar. Soon the Ricardos, the Mertzes, and (special guest) actor [[Fred MacMurray]] set out together to strike it rich. However, when things go out wrong, it\u2019s a race to see who gets to the claims office. (Also appearing in this show is MacMurray's wife, [[June Haver]].)\n| LineColor = 1B548A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H4\n| Title = Lucy Wins a Race Horse\n| Aux3 = December 1957\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1958|2|3}}\n| ShortSummary = Lucy wins a race horse for Little Ricky. In order to keep the horse, Lucy enters the horse in a race at [[Roosevelt Raceway (harness racing)|Roosevelt Raceway]] with the help of [[Betty Grable]]. [[Harry James]], Betty's husband, also guest stars.\n| LineColor = 1B548A\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H5\n| Title = Lucy Goes to Sun Valley\n| Aux3 = February 1958\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1958|4|14}}\n| ShortSummary = Lucy and Ethel go to [[Sun Valley, Idaho|Sun Valley]] without Ricky and Fred. While in Sun Valley, the girls meet [[Fernando Lamas]] and Lucy hatches a scheme to make Ricky jealous enough to join them.\n| LineColor = 1B548A\n}}\n|}\n\n===Season 2 (1958\u201359)===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#B8B6AD; width:30px\"| N\u00ba\n! style=\"background:#B8B6AD\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#B8B6AD; width:135px\"| Film date\n! style=\"background:#B8B6AD; width:135px\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H6\n| Title = Lucy Goes to Mexico\n| Aux3 = {{date|1958-6-16|mdy}}<br> (Completed)\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1958|10|6}}\n| ShortSummary = Lucy and the gang go with Ricky to Mexico, where he is scheduled to appear in a show with [[Maurice Chevalier]]. Meanwhile, Lucy just happens to find herself in a [[bullfight]].\n| LineColor = B8B6AD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H7\n| Title = Lucy Makes Room for Danny\n| Aux3 = {{date|1958-9-19|mdy}}\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1958|12|1}}\n| ShortSummary = The Williams family from ''[[The Danny Thomas Show]]'' ([[Danny Thomas]], [[Marjorie Lord]], [[Rusty Hamer]] and [[Angela Cartwright]]) rent Lucy's and Ricky's house because Lucy and Ricky are going to Hollywood. When the Hollywood trip is cancelled, Lucy has to 'Make Room For Danny.' [[Gale Gordon]] also guest stars as a civil court judge who is forced to clean up the mess resulting from a [[snowball fight]] between the two families.\n| LineColor = B8B6AD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H8\n| Title = Lucy Goes to Alaska\n| Aux3 = {{date|1958-12-19|mdy}}<br> (Completed)\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1959|2|9}}\n| ShortSummary = The Ricardos and Merztes go to [[Alaska]], where Lucy does a show with [[Red Skelton]]. Lucy repeatedly falls out of a hammock in their overcrowded bedroom, and panics while flying a small bush airplane with Red.\n| LineColor = B8B6AD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H9\n| Title = Lucy Wants a Career\n| Aux3 = {{date|1959-3-6|mdy}}<br> (Copyrighted)\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1959|4|13}}\n| ShortSummary = Lucy does not want to be a housewife any longer and appears on [[Paul Douglas (actor)|Paul Douglas]]' \"Early Bird Show\" as his \"Girl Friday.\" \nNote: This episode mirrored life for the Arnazes in the 1940s, as Lucy would meet Desi at the train station as she was leaving for work at a movie studio, while Desi would be headed home after working at a nightclub.\n| LineColor = B8B6AD\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H10\n| Title = Lucy's Summer Vacation\n| Aux3 = {{date|1959-5-5|mdy}}<br> (Copyrighted)\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1959|6|8}}\n| ShortSummary = Lucy and Ricky go on a vacation and end up sharing their cabin with [[Howard Duff]] and [[Ida Lupino]].\n| LineColor = B8B6AD\n}}\n|}\n\n===Season 3 (1959\u201360)===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF\"\n|- style=\"color:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#784E46; width:30px\"| N\u00ba\n! style=\"background:#784E46\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#784E46; width:135px\"| Film date\n! style=\"background:#784E46; width:135px\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H11\n| Title = Milton Berle Hides Out at the Ricardos\n| Aux3 = June 1959\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1959|9|25}}\n| ShortSummary = Lucy tries to let [[Milton Berle]] work on his book in peace while he's at the Ricardos' house.\n| LineColor = 784E46\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H12\n| Title = The Ricardos Go to Japan\n| Aux3 = September 1959\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1959|11|27}}\n| ShortSummary = Lucy wants real pearls while in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]], and finds herself dressing up as a [[geisha]] to see that she gets them. [[Bob Cummings]] guest stars.\n| LineColor = 784E46\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H13\n| Title = Lucy Meets the Mustache\n| Aux3 = {{date|1960-3-2|mdy}}<br> (Completed)\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1960|4|1}}\n| ShortSummary = Ricky is depressed because he has not been getting any TV offers lately, so Lucy, Fred, and Ethel try to cheer him up. [[Ernie Kovacs]] and his wife [[Edie Adams]] guest star.\n'''Note''': This is the final episode of the show due to the divorce of Ball and Arnaz, which occurred 2 months after this episode aired. Many people who worked on ''I Love Lucy'' said that they had a feeling this would be the last episode because of the constant fighting between the two even though more episodes were planned to be produced.\n| LineColor = 784E46\n}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Andrews|first=Bart|title=The \"I Love Lucy\" Book|publisher=Doubleday|location=New York|year=1985|isbn=0-385-19033-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ilovelucybook00andr}}\n*{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Elisabeth|title=I love Lucy: Celebrating 50 Years of Love and Laughter|year=2010|origyear=2001|publisher=Running Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=978-0-7624-3983-6}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070604182636/http://www.lucylibrary.com/Pages/ill-guide-1.html Lucy Library - ''\"I Love Lucy\" Episode Guide'']\n*[https://archive.org/details/ILoveLucyOTRBroadcast Audio of ''I Love Lucy'' Radio Episode]\n\n{{I Love Lucy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of I Love Lucy Episodes}}\n[[Category:I Love Lucy episodes| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of American sitcom television series episodes|I Love Lucy]]\n[[Category:I Love Lucy]]\n", "name_user": "Vchimpanzee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeason 5 (1955\u201356):Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_I_Love_Lucy_episodes"}
{"title_page": "Postcolonial theology", "text_new": "'''Postcolonial theology''' is the application of [[Postcolonialism|postcolonial criticism]] to [[Christian theology]]. As is in postcolonial discourse, the term ''postcolonial'' is used without a hyphen, denoting an intellectual reaction against the colonial, instead of being merely sequential to it.{{sfn|Sugirtharajah|2006|p=8}}\n\n== Background ==\nPostcolonial theologians argue that, in the past, the dominant Western form of Christianity is actually determined, shaped, and defined by [[European colonialism]], implying and reinforcing notions such as [[Eurocentrism]], colonial exploitation, and the superiority of European values and culture.{{sfnm|1a1=Amaladoss|1y=2014|1p=107|2a1=Rakotonirina|2y=1999|2p=157|3a1=Steele Ireland|3y=2008|3pp=683\u2013684|4a1=Sugirtharajah|4y=2006|4p=16}} Therefore, critical examination is needed, and alternative interpretations to colonially-tainted narratives need to be constructed.{{sfn|Althaus-Reid|Thompson|1999|pp=i\u2013ii}} This is done by \"revisiting the question of how indigenous cultures can contribute to theology and biblical studies\".{{sfn|Steele Ireland|2008|p=684}}\n\nAlthough [[decolonization]] took place shortly after the [[Second World War]], postcolonial theories did not emerge until the late 1970s. The field of postcolonial theology, correspondingly, did not arise until the 1990s.{{sfn|Kwan|2014|p=9}}\n\nNotable biblical scholars include [[R.&nbsp;S. Sugirtharajah]] and [[Fernando Segovia]] and theologians include [[Musa W. Dube]], [[Wai-Ching Angela Wong]], [[Kwok Pui-lan]], and [[Mayra Rivera]].{{sfnm|1a1=Althaus-Reid|1a2=Thompson|1y=1999|1p=iii|2a1=Kwan|2y=2014|2pp=10\u201313, 18\u201322|3a1=Steele Ireland|3y=2008|3p=683}}\n\n== Biblical criticism ==\nGiven its similarities with literary analysis, it is not surprising that [[biblical studies]] was the first field within Christian studies to apply postcolonial criticism.{{sfn|Kwan|2014|p=9}} Adopting postcolonial critical methods, biblical studies is inspired to take into account issues of \"expansion, domination, and imperialism\" in examining existing biblical interpretation, and in constructing new narratives.{{sfn|Sugirtharajah|2006|p=17}} Indigenous non-Western approaches to theologizing the [[Bible]], previously neglected under the colonial context \"in favor of European methods\", are now revisited, in hope to \"make the Bible comprehensible to the colonized cultures on their own terms\".{{sfn|Steele Ireland|2008|p=684}} Therefore, traditional fields of [[translation]], [[exegesis]], and [[hermeneutics]] in biblical studies have to be reconsidered in light of postcolonial criticism, and non-Western perspectives have to be taken into account, even as focal points.\n\nAmong various scholars, R.&nbsp;S. Sugirtharajah, one of the principal advocates of postcolonial biblical studies, outlined in his book ''The Bible and the Third World'' three hermeneutic approaches which emerged after [[colonialism]]: the native or vernacular approach, the liberation approach, and the postcolonial approach.{{sfn|Sugirtharajah|2001|pp=7\u20139, 175\u2013275}}\n\nThere are certain benefits of applying postcolonial criticism to biblical studies. First, it opens up potential areas and possibilities for interdisciplinary work, enriching the discipline by enabling multiple approaches to bring in their insights. Second, it allows for criticism towards the way things are done, including the principles and presuppositions of the field. In addition, it also avoids detachment from the contemporary world, as work done in the discipline would have to respond to postcolonial contexts.{{sfn|Sugirtharajah|2006|pp=17\u201318}}\n\n== Christian mission historiography ==\nReviewing [[History of Christianity|Christian history]] from a postcolonial critical perspective, [[history]] is realized to be intrinsically more than just impartial facts. As history is essentially a narrative of what happened, it is always an interpretation, which is \"bound by time, place, and the social, political, religious, cultural and economic positions of writers\", and a representation, being an \"interested construction of representation through which power is expressed, reflected, and exercised.\"{{sfn|Rakotonirina|1999|pages=158\u2013159|ps=. Also discussed in {{harvnb|Styers|2009|page=853.}}}}\n\nPostcolonial historical methods, therefore, begins with tracing the development of the dominant narrative, followed by a critical reassessment of the sources and the historiography of the mainstream narrative, and finally teasing out the colonial taints and construct new, alternative narratives.{{sfn|Rakotonirina|1999|pp=162, 173}} This is especially relevant in the history of churches in which missionary work has been heavily involved, as such historiographies tend to have more difficulty in treating Western engagement and local churches from an egalitarian perspective.\n\nAs such, postcolonial criticism contributes to the discipline by putting forth a recognition that current narratives are, or at least are likely to be, shaped by the colonial context. This leads to the awareness that there could be, and should be, alternative representations of those parts of history. Biased historical readings are therefore prevented or at least reduced. {{sfn|Rakotonirina|1999|pp=167\u2013168, 173}}\n\n== Christian theology ==\nGiven the short history of engaging with postcolonial criticism, postcolonial theology as a field of study is still \"in its infancy.\"{{sfn|Kwan|2014|p=9}} It is argued by R.&nbsp;S. Sugirtharajah that its development is further held back by Western reluctance to analyse the theological implications of colonial imperialism.{{sfnm|1a1=Sugirtharajah|1y=2006|1p=19|2a1=Sugirtharajah|2y=2004|2p=22}}\n\nHowever, theologians from the colonized non-West such as [[C.&nbsp;S. Song]] and [[Chung Hyun Kyung]] have long been theologizing with reflection or even resistance against the colonizing West. Interpreted from the perspective of postcolonial criticism, these theologies could be retrospectively categorized as postcolonial theology.{{sfn|Kwan|2014|p=10}} Geographically, they could also be conceptualized according to the three main continents, Africa, Asia, and Latin America. Regional theologies are also influenced by other intellectual trends, such as [[liberation theology]] or [[feminist theology]].\n\n=== African theology ===\nIn Africa, theology is often articulated in one of two aspects: [[inculturation]] and liberation.{{sfn|Martey|1993|xi}} The former is often described as ''[[African theology]]'', which is a term first appeared in 1965 at the [[All Africa Conference of Churches]], and could be identified as \"an attempt by Africans to give theological articulation to their spiritual, political, and economic struggles.\"{{sfn|Pato|1994|153}} The latter is a form of liberation theology and also has an interesting relationship with [[black theology]] in [[North America]]. This would later influence South African theology, especially during and after [[Apartheid]].{{sfn|Pato|1994|p=156}}\n\n=== Asian theology ===\nAsian theology could be understood to be inherently postcolonial,{{sfn|Kwan|2014|p=11}} as it has moved towards a \"discontinuity with Western theology and denounced the usefulness of a theology that allied itself with colonial powers and their dominance.\"{{sfn|Wong|1997}} This resonates with the strong currents of [[nationalism]]. However, since Asian churches have historically been considered under colonial authorities, theologians have had to wrestle with the tension (or even conflict) between religious and national identity. In addition, its focal points include [[indigenization]], liberation from poverty, as well as practical commitment in engaging with the praxis of reality.{{sfn|Wong|2002|p=21}} Hence, the influence of liberation theology is easily notable. \n\nAsian local theologies include [[Dalit theology]] in South Asia, [[Minjung theology]] in South Korea, and [[Burakumin]] theology in Japan.{{sfn|Amaladoss|2014|pp=9\u201310}}\n\n=== Latin American theology ===\nThe Latin American church has been famous for their liberation theology, which influenced numerous theological trends worldwide. It is arguably the earliest postcolonial resistance to western dominance. In comparison, it seems more politically minded, and less concerned in formulating an inculturated theology. Inspired in the 1950s within the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic Church]], it critiques the colonial situation in three ways, addressing how oppression was structurally enforced by the authorities, complicit by the church, and internalized by the oppressed themselves. {{sfn|Keller|Nausner|Rivera|2004|pp=5\u20136, 8}}  \n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n* [[Asian feminist theology]]\n* [[Contextual theology]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Footnotes ===\n{{reflist|22em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n: {{cite journal\n  | last1 = Althaus-Reid\n  | first1 = Marcella\n  | author-link1 = Marcella Althaus-Reid\n  | last2 = Thompson\n  | first2 = T. Jack\n  | date = 1999\n  | title = Editorial\n  | journal = Studies in World Christianity\n  | volume = 5\n  | issue = 2\n  | pages = i\u2013iv\n  | doi = 10.3366/swc.1999.5.2.i\n  | issn = 1354-9901\n  | ref = harv\n}}\n: {{cite encyclopedia\n  | last = Amaladoss\n  | first = Michael\n  | chapter = Asian Theological Trends\n  | editor-last = Wilfred\n  | editor-first = Felix\n  | encyclopedia = The Oxford Handbook of Christianity in Asia\n  | year = 2014\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | location = Oxford\n  | isbn = 978-0-19932-906-9\n  | pages = 104\u2013120\n  | doi = 10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199329069.013.0006\n  | ref = harv\n}}\n: {{cite book\n  | last1 = Keller\n  | first1 = Catherine\n  | author-link1 = Catherine Keller (theologian)\n  | last2 = Nausner\n  | first2 = Michael\n  | last3 = Rivera\n  | first3 = Mayra\n  | author3-link 