nial Criticism\n  | editor-last = Sugirtharajah\n  | editor-first = R.&nbsp;S. \n  | editor-link = R. S. Sugirtharajah\n  | title = The Postcolonial Biblical Reader\n  | year = 2006\n  | location = Oxford\n  | publisher = Blackwell Publishing\n  | pages = 7\u201332\n  | isbn = 978-0-47077-508-0\n  | doi = 10.1002/9780470775080.ch1\n  | ref = harv\n  | author-mask={{long dash}}\n}}\n: {{cite journal\n  |author=Wai-Ching Angela Wong\n  |author-link=Wai-Ching Angela Wong\n  |year=1997\n  |title=Asian Theology in a Changing Asia: Towards an Asian Theological Agenda for the 21st Century\n  |url=http://cca.org.hk/home/ctc/ctc97-cats1/ctc97-cats1g.htm\n  |journal=CTC Bulletin\n  |issue=supplement\n  |location=Shatin, Hong Kong\n  |publisher=Christian Conference of Asia\n  |access-date=23 November 2017\n  |ref={{sfnref|Wong|1997}}\n}}\n: {{cite book\n  |author=Wai-Ching Angela Wong\n  |author-link=Wai-Ching Angela Wong\n  |year=2002\n  |title= \"The Poor Woman\": A Critical Analysis of Asian Theology and Contemporary Chinese Fiction by Women \n  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UGyAQgAACAAJ\n  |location=New York\n  |publisher=Peter Lang\n  |ref={{sfnref|Wong|2002}}\n  |author-mask={{long dash}}\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n: {{cite book\n  |author=Kwok Pui-lan<!-- Kwok is her family name -->\n  |author-link=Kwok Pui-lan\n  |year=2005\n  |title=Postcolonial Imagination and Feminist Theology\n  |location=Louisville, Kentucky\n  |publisher=Westminster John Knox Press\n  |isbn=978-0-664-22883-5\n}}\n: {{cite book\n  | last = Silber\n  | first = Stefan \n  | chapter = Among Sisters. What Postcolonial Studies have to say to Liberation Theology\n  | editor1-last = Strabb\n  | editor1-first = Ute\n  | editor2-last = Rott\n  | editor2-first = Gerhard\n  | editor3-last = Lutz\n  | editor3-first = Ronald\n  | title = Sozialarbeit des S\u00fcdens, Vol. 8: Indigenous and Local Knowledge in Social Work\n  | year = 2020\n  | series = Internationale Sozialarbeit\n  | volume = 8\n  | location = Oldenburg\n  | publisher = Paulo Freire Verlag\n  | pages = 83-96 \n  | isbn = 978-3-86585-916-7\n  | ref = harv\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Postcolonialism]]\n[[Category:Biblical criticism]]\n[[Category:Christian theology]]\n[[Category:World Christianity]]\n", "text_old": "'''Postcolonial theology''' is the application of [[Postcolonialism|postcolonial criticism]] to [[Christian theology]]. As is in postcolonial discourse, the term ''postcolonial'' is used without a hyphen, denoting an intellectual reaction against the colonial, instead of being merely sequential to it.{{sfn|Sugirtharajah|2006|p=8}}\n\n== Background ==\nPostcolonial theologians argue that, in the past, the dominant Western form of Christianity is actually determined, shaped, and defined by [[European colonialism]], implying and reinforcing notions such as [[Eurocentrism]], colonial exploitation, and the superiority of European values and culture.{{sfnm|1a1=Amaladoss|1y=2014|1p=107|2a1=Rakotonirina|2y=1999|2p=157|3a1=Steele Ireland|3y=2008|3pp=683\u2013684|4a1=Sugirtharajah|4y=2006|4p=16}} Therefore, critical examination is needed, and alternative interpretations to colonially-tainted narratives need to be constructed.{{sfn|Althaus-Reid|Thompson|1999|pp=i\u2013ii}} This is done by \"revisiting the question of how indigenous cultures can contribute to theology and biblical studies\".{{sfn|Steele Ireland|2008|p=684}}\n\nAlthough [[decolonization]] took place shortly after the [[Second World War]], postcolonial theories did not emerge until the late 1970s. The field of postcolonial theology, correspondingly, did not arise until the 1990s.{{sfn|Kwan|2014|p=9}}\n\nNotable biblical scholars include [[R.&nbsp;S. Sugirtharajah]] and [[Fernando Segovia]] and theologians include [[Musa W. Dube]], [[Wai-ching Angela Wong]], [[Kwok Pui-lan]], and [[Mayra Rivera]].{{sfnm|1a1=Althaus-Reid|1a2=Thompson|1y=1999|1p=iii|2a1=Kwan|2y=2014|2pp=10\u201313, 18\u201322|3a1=Steele Ireland|3y=2008|3p=683}}\n\n== Biblical criticism ==\nGiven its similarities with literary analysis, it is not surprising that [[biblical studies]] was the first field within Christian studies to apply postcolonial criticism.{{sfn|Kwan|2014|p=9}} Adopting postcolonial critical methods, biblical studies is inspired to take into account issues of \"expansion, domination, and imperialism\" in examining existing biblical interpretation, and in constructing new narratives.{{sfn|Sugirtharajah|2006|p=17}} Indigenous non-Western approaches to theologizing the [[Bible]], previously neglected under the colonial context \"in favor of European methods\", are now revisited, in hope to \"make the Bible comprehensible to the colonized cultures on their own terms\".{{sfn|Steele Ireland|2008|p=684}} Therefore, traditional fields of [[translation]], [[exegesis]], and [[hermeneutics]] in biblical studies have to be reconsidered in light of postcolonial criticism, and non-Western perspectives have to be taken into account, even as focal points.\n\nAmong various scholars, R.&nbsp;S. Sugirtharajah, one of the principal advocates of postcolonial biblical studies, outlined in his book ''The Bible and the Third World'' three hermeneutic approaches which emerged after [[colonialism]]: the native or vernacular approach, the liberation approach, and the postcolonial approach.{{sfn|Sugirtharajah|2001|pp=7\u20139, 175\u2013275}}\n\nThere are certain benefits of applying postcolonial criticism to biblical studies. First, it opens up potential areas and possibilities for interdisciplinary work, enriching the discipline by enabling multiple approaches to bring in their insights. Second, it allows for criticism towards the way things are done, including the principles and presuppositions of the field. In addition, it also avoids detachment from the contemporary world, as work done in the discipline would have to respond to postcolonial contexts.{{sfn|Sugirtharajah|2006|pp=17\u201318}}\n\n== Christian mission historiography ==\nReviewing [[History of Christianity|Christian history]] from a postcolonial critical perspective, [[history]] is realized to be intrinsically more than just impartial facts. As history is essentially a narrative of what happened, it is always an interpretation, which is \"bound by time, place, and the social, political, religious, cultural and economic positions of writers\", and a representation, being an \"interested construction of representation through which power is expressed, reflected, and exercised.\"{{sfn|Rakotonirina|1999|pages=158\u2013159|ps=. Also discussed in {{harvnb|Styers|2009|page=853.}}}}\n\nPostcolonial historical methods, therefore, begins with tracing the development of the dominant narrative, followed by a critical reassessment of the sources and the historiography of the mainstream narrative, and finally teasing out the colonial taints and construct new, alternative narratives.{{sfn|Rakotonirina|1999|pp=162, 173}} This is especially relevant in the history of churches in which missionary work has been heavily involved, as such historiographies tend to have more difficulty in treating Western engagement and local churches from an egalitarian perspective.\n\nAs such, postcolonial criticism contributes to the discipline by putting forth a recognition that current narratives are, or at least are likely to be, shaped by the colonial context. This leads to the awareness that there could be, and should be, alternative representations of those parts of history. Biased historical readings are therefore prevented or at least reduced. {{sfn|Rakotonirina|1999|pp=167\u2013168, 173}}\n\n== Christian theology ==\nGiven the short history of engaging with postcolonial criticism, postcolonial theology as a field of study is still \"in its infancy.\"{{sfn|Kwan|2014|p=9}} It is argued by R.&nbsp;S. Sugirtharajah that its development is further held back by Western reluctance to analyse the theological implications of colonial imperialism.{{sfnm|1a1=Sugirtharajah|1y=2006|1p=19|2a1=Sugirtharajah|2y=2004|2p=22}}\n\nHowever, theologians from the colonized non-West such as [[C.&nbsp;S. Song]] and [[Chung Hyun Kyung]] have long been theologizing with reflection or even resistance against the colonizing West. Interpreted from the perspective of postcolonial criticism, these theologies could be retrospectively categorized as postcolonial theology.{{sfn|Kwan|2014|p=10}} Geographically, they could also be conceptualized according to the three main continents, Africa, Asia, and Latin America. Regional theologies are also influenced by other intellectual trends, such as [[liberation theology]] or [[feminist theology]].\n\n=== African theology ===\nIn Africa, theology is often articulated in one of two aspects: [[inculturation]] and liberation.{{sfn|Martey|1993|xi}} The former is often described as ''[[African theology]]'', which is a term first appeared in 1965 at the [[All Africa Conference of Churches]], and could be identified as \"an attempt by Africans to give theological articulation to their spiritual, political, and economic struggles.\"{{sfn|Pato|1994|153}} The latter is a form of liberation theology and also has an interesting relationship with [[black theology]] in [[North America]]. This would later influence South African theology, especially during and after [[Apartheid]].{{sfn|Pato|1994|p=156}}\n\n=== Asian theology ===\nAsian theology could be understood to be inherently postcolonial,{{sfn|Kwan|2014|p=11}} as it has moved towards a \"discontinuity with Western theology and denounced the usefulness of a theology that allied itself with colonial powers and their dominance.\"{{sfn|Wong|1997}} This resonates with the strong currents of [[nationalism]]. However, since Asian churches have historically been considered under colonial authorities, theologians have had to wrestle with the tension (or even conflict) between religious and national identity. In addition, its focal points include [[indigenization]], liberation from poverty, as well as practical commitment in engaging with the praxis of reality.{{sfn|Wong|2002|p=21}} Hence, the influence of liberation theology is easily notable. \n\nAsian local theologies include [[Dalit theology]] in South Asia, [[Minjung theology]] in South Korea, and [[Burakumin]] theology in Japan.{{sfn|Amaladoss|2014|pp=9\u201310}}\n\n=== Latin American theology ===\nThe Latin American church has been famous for their liberation theology, which influenced numerous theological trends worldwide. It is arguably the earliest postcolonial resistance to western dominance. In comparison, it seems more politically minded, and less concerned in formulating an inculturated theology. Inspired in the 1950s within the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic Church]], it critiques the colonial situation in three ways, addressing how oppression was structurally enforced by the authorities, complicit by the church, and internalized by the oppressed themselves. {{sfn|Keller|Nausner|Rivera|2004|pp=5\u20136, 8}}  \n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\n* [[Asian feminist theology]]\n* [[Contextual theology]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Footnotes ===\n{{reflist|22em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n: {{cite journal\n  | last1 = Althaus-Reid\n  | first1 = Marcella\n  | author-link1 = Marcella Althaus-Reid\n  | last2 = Thompson\n  | first2 = T. Jack\n  | date = 1999\n  | title = Editorial\n  | journal = Studies in World Christianity\n  | volume = 5\n  | issue = 2\n  | pages = i\u2013iv\n  | doi = 10.3366/swc.1999.5.2.i\n  | issn = 1354-9901\n  | ref = harv\n}}\n: {{cite encyclopedia\n  | last = Amaladoss\n  | first = Michael\n  | chapter = Asian Theological Trends\n  | editor-last = Wilfred\n  | editor-first = Felix\n  | encyclopedia = The Oxford Handbook of Christianity in Asia\n  | year = 2014\n  | publisher = Oxford U