 Winner\n| 7.\n| 2009\n| [[Canadian Amateur Championship (snooker)|Canadian Amateur Championship]] <small>(7)</small>\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} John White\n| align=\"center\"| 6\u20131\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* \n* [http://www.snooker.org/plr/bio/arobidoux.shtml Snooker.org profile of Robidoux]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robidoux, Alain}}\n[[Category:Canadian snooker players]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of French descent]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:People from Saint-J\u00e9r\u00f4me, Quebec]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Blacklisted-links|1=\n*http://cuetracker.net/Players/Alain-Robidoux/Career-Total-Statistics\n*:''Triggered by <code>\\bcuetracker\\.net\\b</code> on the local blacklist''|bot=Cyberbot II|invisible=false}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n|name         = Alain Robidoux\n|image        = \n|caption      = \n|birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1960|7|25}}\n|birth_place   = [[Saint-J\u00e9r\u00f4me, Quebec|Saint-J\u00e9r\u00f4me]], [[Quebec]]\n| Sport country = {{CAN}}\n| Nickname     =\n| Professional = 1987\u20132004\n| High ranking = 9 (1996\u20131998)\n| Prize money  = \u00a3637,624<ref name=\"cuetracker.net\">http://cuetracker.net/Players/Alain-Robidoux/Career-Total-Statistics</ref>\n| High break   = '''[[Maximum break|147]]''': <small>1988 European Open</small>\n| Century break = 37<ref name=\"cuetracker.net\"/>\n| Best finish  = {{nowrap|''Runner-up'' <small>([[1996 German Open (snooker)|1996 German Open]])</small>}}\n| Ranking wins = \n| Other wins   = 1\n| World champ  = \n}}\n'''Alain Robidoux''' (born July 25, 1960) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[snooker]] player; he played on the sport's [[World Snooker Tour|main tour]] from 1988 to 2005 and continues to play in events in Canada.\n\n==Career==\nHe was born in [[Saint-J\u00e9r\u00f4me, Quebec|Saint-J\u00e9r\u00f4me]], [[Quebec]] and joined the pro circuit in the late 1980s, playing as a \"non-tournament\" professional. This entitled Robidoux to be listed on official rankings, although he could not play in most competitions. In 1988, Robidoux amassed enough points in the World Championship qualifiers to finish in the top 128 players, and thus allowing him to join the tour full-time.\n\nIn September 1988, Robidoux became only the sixth player ever to record an officially ratified [[Highest snooker break|147 maximum break]] in the qualifiers for the [[Malta Cup|European Open]]. The same month, he won his sole professional title, the [[1988 Canadian Professional Championship|Canadian Professional Championship]]. In October 1988 he reached the semi-finals of the [[1988 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]], where he recovered from 0\u20137 down against [[Alex Higgins]] but ultimately lost the match 7\u20139.\n\nRobidoux's best ranking event performance was reaching the final of the [[1996 German Open (snooker)|1996 German Open]] when he lost 7\u20139 to [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]. In the first round of the [[1996 World Snooker Championship|1996 World Championship]], Robidoux was beaten 3\u201310 by O'Sullivan again. Although he is predominantly right-handed, O'Sullivan played a number of shots with his left hand. This behaviour was described by commentator [[John Virgo]] as O'Sullivan \"[[Take the piss|taking the mick]]\". The matter came to a crux in the eleventh frame, with Robidoux 2\u20138 down, declining to concede the frame, instead continuing to {{Cuegloss|Snookers required|play for snookers}} despite a 43-point deficit with only the pink and black on the table. Robidoux refused to shake O'Sullivan's hand at the end of the match. \nO'Sullivan responded by claiming that he played better with his left hand than Robidoux could with his right.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/anger-over-left-leaning-osullivan-1306125.html|title=Anger over left-leaning O'Sullivan|date=1996-04-22|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2018-12-23}}</ref>\n\nRobidoux reached the semi-finals of the [[1997 World Snooker Championship]], defeating [[Brian Morgan (snooker player)|Brian Morgan]], [[Stefan Mazrocis]] and [[Lee Walker]] before losing to eventual champion [[Ken Doherty]]. He subsequently slid rapidly down the rankings.<ref name=\"SS 2009-05\">{{cite web\n |url= http://snookerscene.blogspot.com/2009/05/past-masters2.html\n |title=Past Masters #2\n |last=Hendon\n |first=David\n |work=Snooker Scene Blog: News, Opinion and Insight from the Green Baize\n |date=26 May 2009\n |location=Halesowen, England\n |publisher=Snooker Scene Magazine\n |accessdate=2010-01-17\n}}</ref> Robidoux blamed his decline on the destruction of his favourite [[Cue stick|cue]],<ref name=\"SS 2009-05\" /> which he referred to as \"the Eel\". But when he took it back for repairs to the man he bought it from, he objected to Robidoux having \nfixed a sponsor's logo to the butt end and smashed the cue into pieces. Several years later, Robidoux was asked whether the passage of time may have eased his anger towards the cue maker; he responded \"I want to kill him.\"<ref name=\"SS 2009-05\"/>\n[https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Robidoux+at+a+dead+end.-a060684232 Robidoux at a dead end.]\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[Snooker season 1987/1988|1987/<br/>88]]\n! [[Snooker season 1988/1989|1988/<br/>89]]\n! [[Snooker season 1989/1990|1989/<br/>90]]\n! [[Snooker season 1990/1991|1990/<br/>91]]\n! [[Snooker season 1991/1992|1991/<br/>92]]\n! [[Snooker season 1992/1993|1992/<br/>93]]\n! [[Snooker season 1993/1994|1993/<br/>94]]\n! [[Snooker season 1994/1995|1994/<br/>95]]\n! [[Snooker season 1995/1996|1995/<br/>96]]\n! [[Snooker season 1996/1997|1996/<br/>97]]\n! [[Snooker season 1997/1998|1997/<br/>98]]\n! [[Snooker season 1998/1999|1998/<br/>99]]\n! [[Snooker season 1999/2000|1999/<br/>00]]\n! [[Snooker season 2000/2001|2000/<br/>01]]\n! [[Snooker season 2